node.text:
This meeting went better than I could have expected. Lark may sound mean in these clips, but the sounds she is making are just her letting Fig know she’s a little uncomfortable and setting some boundaries. After about 30 minutes they spent the rest of the day napping under the couch together. It’s a huge sign of trust to sleep so close to one another! 
-
Can you spot one major difference between them? Notice how much larger Fig is and how much fuller his coat is than hers? Fur farm foxes have been bred to be significantly larger than wild North American foxes.
#larkthefox

node.text: Yesterday Herbal made it through his surgery, but around 9pm his heart stopped. The vets are not exactly sure why he crashed so suddenly, especially after it had been serval hours since he had woken from surgery. My heart aches since he was truly my little buddy. I thought it would be nice to share with all of you the first day I brought him home almost three years ago.

node.text:
After weeks of not being able to find a vet specialized enough to care for Herbal I resorted to making a story begging for help. I was lucky enough to catch the eye of a wonderful vet in Atlanta, Jessica, who was kind enough to walk me through what I needed and pointed me to the Univerity Of Florida Small Mammal Hosptial, where Herbal has been receiving intensive care since Monday. 
-
The staff at UF was able to get him stable, eating, and after a CT scan they were finally able to identify the cause of his issues.
-
Dental disease can be genetic or due to improper care. In Herbal’s case it’s both. Herbal came to me as a neglect case and was fed exclusively hamster food by his previous owner. This poor diet has lead him to where he is now. Chinchilla’s diet needs to be 80% hay to help keep their teeth and digestive tract healthy. Even two years of proper diet and care was not enough to revert the damage that was done by his previous diet. 
-
When adopting an animal please make sure to do proper research on the care that animal requires to be their healthiest. Chinchillas have a lifespan of around 20 years, Herbal is only 3 and will now live with this condition the rest of his life.

node.text:
Yesterday I had the pleasure of visiting @art.by.keith. Newt and Ferngully are both ambassador animals that are in training right now! So they have been accompanying me to any “controlled” social outing I can manage to bring them to. This helps to get them accustomed to new environments and people and helps them to be more confident as adults for educational programs! 
-
I’m beyond proud of little Newton, who was more than happy to allow strangers to take him for a walk around the studio. He took treats very nicely, and made a few new friends. One who he was particularly fond of.
-
This was a great experience for them so thank you @oakandinktattoostudio for helping aid their socialization process and being wonderful hosts.

The small sounds he makes before dropping the treat is a sound reserved for calling over loved ones. How sweet is that?

node.text:
Many of you have been asking about Lark’s introduction to Fern. If you have read our previous posts you’ll know that Lark lost her litter of kits earlier in the year. When taking in Ferngully I hoped that she would adopt him as her own as Juniper has done with kits in the past. Both male and female foxes will often parent babies even if they are not their own. 
-
I apologize that there is not more footage, but their introductions to each other have had to be carefully monitored. Prior to face to face introductions we started with allowing her to view him through play pens and carriers. She seemed interested, but only curious as to what he was. Not interested in the same way that we have seen foxes display when they’re are excited about a new baby.
-
After I was sure she wasn’t showing signs of aggression I allowed them to interact freely. She would occasionally show some interest, but spent most of her time asking him to give her space. Because of this I’ve come to the sad conclusion that she is not up to mothering him in the same way that we’ve seen in previous years. However, it seems that she is still too stressed by her environment to focus on anything other than her own safety.
-
When looking at this long term it does not mean that things will not change. Lark is receptive to the other adult foxes and once Fern is old enough, he and Lark could still be part of the same group as I’m fairly certain they will get along once boundaries are established.
-
So for now, she will be able to interact with him from afar and we will try again once he’s a little bigger.

Happy 4th to those of you in the United States! I know many of us like to celebrate this day outdoors and finish up with some fireworks once the sun goes down, but remember to be considerate  of the wildlife in your neighborhood.
- 
Rabbits can die of heart attacks from the sounds of fireworks. Birds can become disoriented and fly into windows. Nursing mammals panic and abandon their young. 
-
This time of year is dreaded not just by wildlife rehabilitators, but also veterinarians’ offices, livestock farms, and domestic animal shelters due to the massive increase in injuries and runaways of pets caused by fireworks. Fireworks also cause many wildfires, outdoor waste, and can be upsetting to those with PTSD.
-
If fireworks are important to you, please consider attending a public, professional fireworks show. Although these events do still have an impact on wildlife, they do help lessen the stress by being contained to one area.
-
